messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full request path:
- /cms/admin/group/{gid}

All HTTP methods acceptable:
- false

Per-method acceptability (based on the code, not runtime/Flask implicit behavior):
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- The app registers a top-level blueprint at url_prefix="/cms" in app.create_app -> register_blueprints (app/__init__.py).
- The cms blueprint (app/api/cms/__init__.py) registers admin_api at url_prefix="/admin".
- The endpoint in question is defined in app/api/cms/admin.py with the route decorator @admin_api.route("/group/<int:gid>", ...).
  - That yields the combined path /cms + /admin + /group/<int:gid> -> /cms/admin/group/{gid} (path parameter shown as {gid}).
- The file defines three separate view functions mapped to that same path:
  - get_group: @admin_api.route("/group/<int:gid>") — no methods parameter (defaults to GET) → GET is accepted.
  - update_group: @admin_api.route("/group/<int:gid>", methods=["PUT"]) → PUT is accepted.
  - delete_group: @admin_api.route("/group/<int:gid>", methods=["DELETE"]) → DELETE is accepted.
- The code does not explicitly declare HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, POST, or PATCH handlers for this path, so per the instructions (base on code only, not framework implicit behaviors) those methods are marked false.
- "All HTTP methods acceptable" is false because the code explicitly registers only specific methods for this path.
